Conclusions

During reading our brain predicts upcoming words. Predictability (probability of guessing the next word) is usually estimated by performing cloze experiments, where participants read incomplete statements and have to complete them with one word. During the task, the only information subject can use is the preceding context. To estimate the predictability of one word in a context, it is necessary to ask several participants, and then calculate the proportion of correct answers. Cloze-task is then an expensive experiment, and results are only valid for those words in that especific context.

Over the last years, different approaches have been taken to automatically estimate this human predictability. Here we analysed different ways of predicting words computationally, using Natural Language Processing algorithms (LSA, word2vec, n-grams) to explore different aspects of the human predictability (semantic, syntactic, mnemonic).

We evaluated the incorporation of these computational measures, both by themselves or combined on Linear Mixed Models with eye movements as dependent variables. Results show that these computational estimations of the word predictability have very good performance and can be used to replace the human predictability in the used models. Furthermore, this is a step forward in understanding and separating the contribution of the different cues we use to predict words.

The Predictability is the probability of knowing a future word before reading it. It is usually estimated based on a cloze-task procedure, where a big group of subjects answers the most probable word given a previous context. Although its simplicity, estimating it becomes very expensive when dealing with long texts.

In the present study, we aim to understand predictability through the analysis of eye-movements (in particular, gaze duration) and its correlation with a big set of co-variables using Linear Mixed Models (LMM). For this, we recorded subjects reading long texts (~3000 words) and fitted LMMs with and without the cloze-predictability.

During the last years different approaches have been taken in order to simulate this cloze-predictability. These simulations would be both interesting and useful in the research field: interesting because they may help us to understand the sources of predictions, and useful because they could be use as replacement for understanding brain processes underlying predictions during reading.
We implemented 3 algorithms for simulating the word predictability: LSA, word2vec and ngram. We analysed the contribution of their results when added to the LMM.

Reading corpus: 7 short natural stories (without any external modification) with around 3000 words each. Eye-movements (36 healthy subjects recorded with an EyeLink 1000) were analysed using the gaze duration while reading these stories on a 19-inch PC monitor.

Cloze task: an on-line experiment was implemented in order to reach a high number of responses. We estimated the predictability of half of the words of our corpus, mainly the content words (see Box 1).

Linear Mixed Models: We fitted a LMM with co-variables from the fixed word, and a saccade parameter [Kamienkowski, 2016a]. This model will serve as the baseline for comparing those with cloze and computational predictability as co-variable

Computer estimations: we used three different algorithms to predict words: LSA, word2vec and ngrams [Bianchi 2014, Kamienkowski, 2016b]. The training corpus consist in over 28.000 fiction books. Predictions were performed as follow:

LSA and word2vec: both algorithms consist in projecting words in a 300-dimensional space. This allows us to estimate word predictability as the cosine distance between words. Using a n-size window (varying n from 1 to 100) of previous words we estimated LSA-predictability with two different approaches: distance to the resultant vector of the context and mean of the distances from the target word with all the words from the context [Box 2].

flowPara.flowSpan: we used N-grams with n = [1, 7] [Box 3] and mixed it with a unigram cache. That is, we added a within-text unigram memory to the transition probability generated with the N-gram. We optimised three parameters for this prediction: the N for training and prediction, the mixture coefficients (lambda) and the smoothing parameter from the unigram cach calculation (Equation 1)

- Massive on-line cloze-predictability behaves as expected from classical controled experiments
- Despite a good correlation with the cloze-predictability, W2V is a bad predictor for eye movements.
- W2V may be explaining a different part of cloze-pred

Optimiaztion
- LSA (50) captures some variability from the EM.
- Nonetheless, it is bad replacement of cloze-pred, since It has no effect on the LMM results when added together.
- Despite a high correlation with frequency, N-grams + cache could serve a partial replacement for cloze-pred
- This is also seen in the remef models, M3 and M4 where significance of cloze-pred is reduced when N-gram effect have been fixed by removing its estimate from data.
